The description here given ol the Roman contract system-il we may use that expression to indicate the aggregate os actionable agreements-is somewhat misleading. It must not be supposed thatin the time os Justinian‚ or even ol Gaius no agreement was ground to support an action which was neither expressed in the lorrn of stipulation‚ nor belonged to one or other ol the classes ol Real and Consensual contracta. There had been a considerable advance iu two directions since the time when usage had restricted the term ‘contract' to denote the four classes ol agreement enumerated in Title 13. Between the establishment ol the EmpIre and the age ol the last great classical jurists the principle of the Real contracta had received a great development by the recognition ol the rule, that where one party to any bilateral agreement whatsoever had perlonned what he had undertaken he had always a remedy by action to enlorce performance by the other.
